### 8. Exception Handling — `ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsValidationError` (lines 110–118)

Manual `try/catch` instead of the framework's `Assert.ThrowsException`. The pattern works, but if someone removes the `Assert.Fail` line, the test silently passes when no exception is thrown.

```csharp
// ❌ Current
try
{
    processor.ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.Fail("Expected an exception but none was thrown");
}
catch (ValidationException ex)
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
}
```

**Fix:** Use MSTest's built-in exception assertion:

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ValidationException>(
    () => processor.ProcessOrder(order));

Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
```

**Risk:** Fragile — removing the `Assert.Fail` makes the test pass even when no exception is thrown. The built-in pattern is immune to this.

